e periphery of the west and its simultaneous self-consciousness as a colonial power shaped its artistic, cultural and national identity as a heterogenous, multi-ethnic empire. It also explores the extent to which cultural practitioners participated in the discursive matrices that advanced Russia’s colonial machinery on the one hand and critiqued and challenged it on the other, especially in territories that were themselves on the fault lines between the east and the west.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aOrientalism in art. 0aOrientalismzRussiaxHistoryy18th century. 0aOrientalismzRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aOrientalismzRussiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aOrientalismzSoviet Union. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aEdward Said.  aOrientalism.  aRussian Empire.  aRussian art and architecture.  aart reception.  acolonialism.  acultural history.  adecolonization.  arace and ethnicity.1 aArbuthnot, Mollie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalagurov, Nikita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChuchvaha, Hanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGasper-Hulvat, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Ekaterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufmann, Katrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeigh, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeigh, Allison, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMilam, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNedd, Andrew M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoberts, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca